de.<br><br>A tear in the fabric of time and space opened up and allowed the Feir`Dal ranger, the Koada`Dal wizard, and half elven druid to appear within the obsidian ring.  Millikin habitually turned and looked up at the statue of the dragon guardian.  After an exchange of coin and word of thanks, the druid traced a rectangular pattern in midair and vanished in a swirl of mist. <br><br>The biting chill wind was the first thing to grab Shiobahn's attention as she examined the landscape.  For as far as the eye could see was snow, looming black cliffsides or mountain peaks.  She pulled her cloak closer around her form and followed Millikin's direction in the south.<br><br>  &quot;The mad sorceror Velketor makes his lair in one of the caves that way.  The Coldain say he sometimes kidnaps their people for experiments and even his own people, the Kromzek spurn him.  I've explored the caves a bit.  He has golem constructs and gargoyles guarding the entrances to his castle.  Mostly I've encountered giant spiders or kobolds there though.  There's also whispers of a dissident sect of Coldain making a hideout in the caves out here.  I've not had the chance to confirm that as of yet though.&quot;<br><br>  &quot;It sounds as if you've gotten involved in the politics of the Coldain, Cousin.  Despite your experiences in Freeport.&quot;  Shiobahn smiled to the ranger.<br><br>Millikin shrugged slightly.  &quot;They are at war with the those who encroach upon the Tunarean Court.  'The enemy of my enemy is my friend' I suppose you could say.  And Thurgadin, our destination, is due north.  Barring any accidents or delays, we should reach the city in an hour or so.  It gets cold out here at night.&quot;<br><br>As the two headed north, the ranger continued her discourse of the local inhabitants and creatures of the area and how to best combat or avoid them.  Shardwurms roamed near the mountain peaks near their lairs within and seemed to blend into the background with their white scales.  Until they unleashed their chilling breath weapon.  The primitive yaklike humanoid tizmak made their home in a network of caves in the western mountain sides.  Feral kodiaks wandered the eastern and southern mountain range.  Finally Shiobahn saw the outline of a Coldain guard tower near a river and faintly heard the roar of a waterfall.  Out of the corner of her eye, she saw a shadowy outline rushing towards them... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub51.ezboard.com/uautumncrescendo.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Autumn Crescendo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>this one time, at bard camp...</span><br>  Posts: 354<br> <font color=#333333>(7/14/02 2:54:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub51.ezboard.com/flormani79848frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse (one chapter in a larger story)</span><hr size=1>   Despite the enchantment of a magical skin Shiobahn was slapped to the side by a large paw that nearly encompassed half of her torso.  The second slap hit her and again though unscathed by her shielding it did not stop her from getting a bit dazed.  It would break through in a few more hits, but what was it.  Pulling herself up from the deep snow that bogged the pass, her eyes lifted to face her assailant, and she was face to face with the Kodiak.  Its eyes gleamed with raw fury, and its claws were in full extension from its paws, and again it tried mauling and maiming in large swinging strokes, a third and fourth glancing off her shield.  <br><br>  Millikin was swift on the scene; she knew this type of combat was not one her cousin would last in.  Shiobahn was uttering the words to shackle the beast while dodging blows, and just as the spell took off Millikin was in control.  Energy crackled from the duel blades she wielded and she went into a fast and furious combat, the beast scarcely landing a solid hit on the nimble elf.  Shiobahn regained her composure as swiftly as she could, reaching her arms out as she called upon the power of the elements and invoked them into a fiery rain pelting down upon the Kodiak in waves.  Before she could even utter another spell though the beast was run through and crumpled to the ground.<br><br>  Millikin gave a quick assessment of her cousin, assuring that there was nothing more than minor damage to be had.  Her eyes scanned down either side of the pass before falling more particularly on the snow.  Her tracking skills were keen and she wanted to make certain that their attacker had been alone.  Satisfied he was simply a wanderer she glanced back at her cousin.  <br><br>&quot;Perhaps you will want to use a shield of invisibility until we are safely at the city lines.&quot;<br><br>Shiobahn nodded in agreement, glanced around a moment with some trepidation, then withdrew her spell book flipping with haste to the area she had her invisibility spell marked.  It took but a second to refresh the incantation to her mind before she felt certain enough to cast it.  Her fingers traced a series of runes in the air and in a moment she was cloaked in the stealth of invisibility.  <br><br>&quot;I am ready.&quot;  Shiobahn murmured to her cousin.<br><br>&quot;This way then.&quot;  Millikin gave a small tilt of her head to indicate direction before again into the snow.<br><br>  Shiobahn marveled at how many people she saw in a mimicked fashion, skirting in the shadows of invisibility with her.  She touched the slim bone hoop earring Quasqueton had brought her as a gift from his travels, the enchantment allowing her the sight to spot those hiding in the folds of invisibility.  It was good to know she was not so alone as she lurked in the cold wastes.  The frozen stream caught her attention ahead.  The water was crisp and an icy blue, and the sounds of the waterfall that kept it moving came into hearing distance.  Curving around the river they ended up at the base of the falls and Millikin turned to regard her cousin.<br><br>&quot;Follow me around back, we will go behind the falls.&quot;  She called out over the heavy rush of water.<br><br>&quot;Behind?  This is what you spoke of when you mentioned their protection from the Giants, yes?&quot;<br><br>  Millikin nodded then slipped behind the falls, and passing by the guards that held the outposts at the front of the city.  Shiobahn scampered behind the waterfall as well and blinked coming into site of the Dwarves.  She was raised not so far from the city of Kaladim, and these Dwarves looked nothing like the ones of her homelands.  Their skin was so pale it was near transparent coming from years of never seeing the sun.  Their features were harsher, and more chiseled, almost a reflection of the world that surrounded them.  It was after a series of gates that the two parted ways.  A brief discussion on where the basic essentials could be found took place.<br><br>&quot;Be safe cousin, and good luck finding Quas…&quot;  Shiobahn gave the ranger a quick embrace.<br><br>&quot;Thank you.&quot;  Millikin murmured, taken aback by the affection of her cousin.  &quot;I should not have too much trouble finding him, he leaves a trail of disaster in his wake.&quot;<br><br>&quot;I know, isn't it fantastic?&quot;  Shiobahn beamed.<br><br>&quot;I will never understand wizards…&quot;  Millikin muttered as she walked off in search of a few fletching supplies for the road. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub51.ezboard.com/umillikinerreene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Millikin Erreene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lor Mani Friend</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#333333>(7/17/02 1:09:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub51.ezboard.com/flormani79848frm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=15.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Curse (one chapter in a larger story)</span><hr size=1> Millikin exited Thurgadin, Shiobahn's letter was safely stowed in her backpack.  By nightfall she had reached the Eastern Wastes and the temperature was dropping rapidly.  Millikin looked at the rapidly darkening sky, a storm was approaching.  She smiled grimly to herself as she made her way to a Coldain shelter she knew was nearby.  An explosion and flash of orange light caught her attention.  The aroma of burning flesh and charred fur assailed her sense of smell and made her eyes water.<br><br>The ranger quickly headed in that direction.  On occasion she saw the corpses of tundra kodiaks, dire wolves, orc scouts, even a snow griffin.  She sighed inwardly as she knelt down and inspected the snow for tracks.  None were visible, which means the perpetrator was most likely a spellcaster.  Why didn't people make use of the remains?  Corpses tended to attract scavengers.  Soon the snow was falling faster and the wind grew louder so that she almost didn't hear the approaching Kromrif.<br><br>  &quot;Die Outlander!&quot;  The sight of forged velium flashed before her and ripped through the chain mesh tunic she wore, spilling blood on the white snow in front of her.  The ranger fell backwards and immediately rolled sideways to avoid the follow-up strike.  In moments she was on her feet, weapons drawn, a healing cantra passed her lips and the wounds immediately began to close.  Millikin circled behind the Kromrif as he turned with a slashing arc towards her.  In a blur of motion, she ran between his legs and slashed at the back of his knees.  The giant howled in fury and lashed out with his fist to connect with a solid crunch to her back as she ran in front of him.  The ranger stumbled a few paces and spun around in time to block his weapon thrust and counterblow to his elbow with Swiftwind.  The giant was wielding a dagger, but the blade was long enough to be considered a short sword by the elf's estimation.  The Kromrif scout swung his foot sideways to sweep the elf to the ground and was mildly surprised to see she only staggered slightly.  <br><br>  &quot;By Rallos, you are more resilient than I expected, Outlander.  Mayhap there is a place for you alive as a servant.&quot;  The giant bantered as he saw the outline of the ranger backing away, he could hear her breath was ragged and grinned thinking this encounter would be over all too soon.<br><br>  &quot;I've no intention of finding out.&quot;  Swords still in hand, the elven ranger traced a sigil in midair.  Magical energy coalesced briefly then flickered out.  Somehow she had miscast the spell.  &quot;Valdayana's thrice damned curse.&quot;  She sighed again.  Swiftly wiping her blades and sheathing them, Millikin turned and ran relying on the darkness from the approaching storm for cover.  The giant quickly followed, though his vision was not as good as the elf's.  The protective enchantment the ranger had enabling her to regenerate from injuries at an accelerated rate without calling upon a healing cantra would fade soon.  She quickly pulled herself up into the branches of a tree and readied her bow.  Soon she saw the Kromrif's outline and took aim.  The arrow tore through the giant's chest and he staggered.  He reached for the piece of wood and ripped it out, cursing.  The arrowhead was barbed.  Another arrow found itself imbedded in his shoulder and a third grazed his temple.  Hastily the giant turned and ran.  Millikin watched his departure as she dropped down from the tree more intent on finding cover from the approaching storm than giving chase.  She smelled smoke from a nearby campfire, and unless she was hopelessly lost she was fairly sure that Garadain Glacierbane's encampment wasn't too far away.  She headed in that direction.<br><br>~~~~~<br><br>The Kromrif scout grumbled as he made his way back to Kael Drakkel, limping and bleeding.  Far too many outlanders of late have been seen in the area and working with the Coldain.  And the fact that he had been bested by one would not be viewed favorably by Sergeant Tellsren.<br><br>  &quot;Kromrif.  I want a few words with you.&quot;<br><br>  &quot;Eh?&quot;  The giant turned around and looked down to see a small framed creature hidden beneath a hooded travel cloak and his brow furrowed.  Another outlander.  The person was armed with a stave of some sort, he couldn't quite make out the details.  His first thought was to step on the person and move on, hoping this one's death would salvage his reputation somewhat after his defeat at the hands of the Feir`Dal.<br><br>  &quot;The ranger you fought earlier.  Her blood is still on your weapon, no?&quot;  <br><br>The giant glanced down at the dagger in his hand.  The blood was slowly drying on the velium blade.<br><br>  &quot;Yes.  What of it?&quot;  The giant rumbled, tightening the grip on the hilt in anticipation of challenge.<br><br>  &quot;I require that elf's blood.&quot;  The speaker spoke quietly.<br><br>  &quot;Then get it from her yourself, Outlander.&quot;  The Kromrif sneered.<br><br>  &quot;I do not have the time for such menial activities.&quot;  <br><br>  &quot;You mean you lack the ability to get it from her.  Begone, before I crush your bones to dust.  You've wasted enough of my time.&quot;   The frost giant turned and headed down the ramp to Kael, ignoring the arcane syllables carried on the wind when suddenly he stopped.<br><br>  &quot;On second thought ... here.&quot;  The Kromrif scout handed the dagger to the stranger. <br><br>  &quot;Bel' la dos.&quot;  A faint note of ironic humor laced the speaker's tone as she whispered an arcane phrase and vanished from sight.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub51.ezboard.com/umillikinerreen